links.title: Enterprise reports in-line Q3 even as crude pipeline transport volumes plunge
links.description: Enterprise Products Partners +0.5% pre-market after reporting Q3 earnings of $0.48/unit, up from $0.46 in the year-ago period and matching analyst expectations, and adjusted EBITDA rose 1.8% Y/Y to $2.06B.Q3 revenues fell 13% to $6.92B, missing estimates, as crude pipeline volumes fell 26% to 1.7M bbl/day from 2.3M a year ago, with the pandemic hurting oil prices and leaving midstream companies with fewer barrels to transport after producers cut production.Q3 distributable cash flow remained steady at $1.65B, which provided 1.7x coverage of the $0.445/unit cash distribution and resulted in $669M of retained DCF.Co-CEO A.J.

links.title: Why Energy Transfer Cut Their Distribution
links.description: Energy Transfer's ( ET) 50% distribution cut announced late on Monday surprised most observers. Given the comfortable 1.4-1.5X DCF coverage this year and next, many felt that there was little pressure to reduce it. However, the persistently high yield (18% before the announcement), reflected widespread investor skepticism around its sustainability.
